1
00:00:03,939 --> 00:00:07,703
Good afternoon, and welcome to Realistic Performances and Games.

2
00:00:08,945 --> 00:00:13,930
Fair warning, I have been told this talk is a bit chewy, so strap in.

3
00:00:16,813 --> 00:00:20,537
There is a perception out there that the average game is mindless entertainment,

4
00:00:20,977 --> 00:00:25,322
with at best a thin story, cardboard cutout characters, and stilted acting.

5
00:00:27,153 --> 00:00:30,215
But many companies have been working tirelessly against that stigma.

6
00:00:30,776 --> 00:00:35,400
At Naughty Dog, where I've been for over seven years, we work hard to ensure our performances

7
00:00:35,540 --> 00:00:40,524
are believable, emotionally relevant to the player, and blend with our gameplay as seamlessly

8
00:00:40,624 --> 00:00:41,125
as possible.

9
00:00:42,886 --> 00:00:47,510
I'm Ryan James, and I work at Naughty Dog in a somewhat unique position, as lead editor.

10
00:00:48,495 --> 00:00:51,098
Aside from writing and directing some of our content,

11
00:00:51,518 --> 00:00:53,240
it's my job to keep the rest of the team,

12
00:00:53,360 --> 00:00:55,081
or to help the rest of the team create

13
00:00:55,282 --> 00:00:57,864
and maintain performances that feel like what you'd expect

14
00:00:57,904 --> 00:01:00,727
from an edited movie, even when they're fully interactive.

15
00:01:02,128 --> 00:01:03,769
But what makes a realistic performance?

16
00:01:04,950 --> 00:01:06,952
In Naughty Dog, it means a character needs

17
00:01:06,992 --> 00:01:09,294
to feel vulnerable, nuanced, and human,

18
00:01:10,996 --> 00:01:12,257
which means we're often focused

19
00:01:12,397 --> 00:01:14,039
on how natural every movement feels.

20
00:01:14,814 --> 00:01:17,275
meaning how the character moves and how they speak

21
00:01:17,716 --> 00:01:20,137
needs to feel emotionally and physically relatable.

22
00:01:21,197 --> 00:01:23,198
And of course, they also have to look realistic,

23
00:01:23,578 --> 00:01:25,399
which takes labor from everyone to get right.

24
00:01:27,721 --> 00:01:28,841
Which is our entire goal.

25
00:01:29,581 --> 00:01:32,543
Naughty Dog's games strive to intertwine story and gameplay

26
00:01:32,863 --> 00:01:35,564
so the player experiences a seamless performance,

27
00:01:35,865 --> 00:01:38,466
which we call the active cinematic experience.

28
00:01:41,116 --> 00:01:43,717
We like to provide the player with emotional investment

29
00:01:43,797 --> 00:01:46,318
and motivation behind the moment-to-moment gameplay.

30
00:01:47,099 --> 00:01:49,700
This is largely done through non-interactive cut scenes,

31
00:01:50,240 --> 00:01:52,261
but because we strive to keep the player in control

32
00:01:52,301 --> 00:01:53,301
as often as possible,

33
00:01:53,821 --> 00:01:55,502
a lot of those drama and character moments

34
00:01:55,602 --> 00:01:58,243
end up paying off on the stick, as we call it.

35
00:02:01,282 --> 00:02:02,982
But figuring out which beats belong where

36
00:02:03,422 --> 00:02:04,923
and pulling off the execution of them

37
00:02:05,323 --> 00:02:06,764
requires a lot of iteration.

38
00:02:07,584 --> 00:02:09,905
And at Naughty Dog, one of our biggest strengths

39
00:02:10,085 --> 00:02:13,006
is our willingness to retool or even throw away content,

40
00:02:13,386 --> 00:02:14,786
including captured performances,

41
00:02:15,227 --> 00:02:16,947
if it will make the player's experience better.

42
00:02:18,848 --> 00:02:20,608
Even when deadlines are extremely tight,

43
00:02:21,189 --> 00:02:23,489
our company culture encourages people to speak up

44
00:02:23,569 --> 00:02:24,830
if they think something isn't working

45
00:02:25,330 --> 00:02:26,691
and take advantage of our tools

46
00:02:26,731 --> 00:02:29,391
which enable quick alterations to try out new ideas.

47
00:02:30,641 --> 00:02:33,084
This means all of the narrative content that we capture

48
00:02:33,264 --> 00:02:36,248
is prone to changing, even after it goes into the game.

49
00:02:37,110 --> 00:02:39,713
And sometimes, these alterations happen so quickly

50
00:02:39,793 --> 00:02:40,895
that their trickle-down effects

51
00:02:40,935 --> 00:02:42,216
get lost in the daily shuffle.

52
00:02:43,793 --> 00:02:47,696
Thus, it is up to the editorial team to constantly chase change,

53
00:02:48,336 --> 00:02:50,698
tracking and managing each edited performance

54
00:02:50,818 --> 00:02:53,260
in its various evolutions over the course of development,

55
00:02:54,201 --> 00:02:56,182
in order to ensure that when the player gets their hands

56
00:02:56,242 --> 00:02:58,924
on the game, our characters' interactions still feel

57
00:02:59,204 --> 00:03:01,406
like the authentic human moments we'd intended them

58
00:03:01,446 --> 00:03:02,827
to be when we first captured them.

59
00:03:04,583 --> 00:03:07,464
So today I wanted to share some of the techniques we've used

60
00:03:07,844 --> 00:03:09,105
and challenges we've encountered

61
00:03:09,505 --> 00:03:11,566
when creating realistic performances in games

62
00:03:12,126 --> 00:03:13,407
while allowing them to change

63
00:03:13,547 --> 00:03:14,528
over the course of development.

64
00:03:15,988 --> 00:03:17,249
Oh, and just a heads up,

65
00:03:17,749 --> 00:03:20,090
spoiler warning for most of our games.

66
00:03:24,168 --> 00:03:26,629
Here at Naughty Dog, we don't develop the story second.

67
00:03:27,269 --> 00:03:29,309
Since we shoot and implement narrative material

68
00:03:29,369 --> 00:03:32,230
in small batches, capturing progressively with the actors

69
00:03:32,290 --> 00:03:35,510
for easily a year or more, our story in fact comes together

70
00:03:35,610 --> 00:03:36,731
right alongside design.

71
00:03:38,151 --> 00:03:40,691
Of course, it takes many months of pre-production

72
00:03:40,711 --> 00:03:42,032
before we can shoot anything.

73
00:03:42,732 --> 00:03:44,412
Our directors and writers first juggle

74
00:03:44,432 --> 00:03:46,312
developing story macros with design,

75
00:03:46,732 --> 00:03:48,273
overseeing the creation of characters

76
00:03:48,313 --> 00:03:50,053
that offer varied gameplay mechanics,

77
00:03:50,433 --> 00:03:52,453
and casting actors to embody those characters.

78
00:03:53,885 --> 00:03:55,986
But, as soon as we have enough material written,

79
00:03:56,266 --> 00:03:58,026
we jump in headfirst with our actors

80
00:03:58,066 --> 00:04:00,147
to capture story beats via motion capture

81
00:04:00,227 --> 00:04:01,107
and dialogue recording.

82
00:04:02,048 --> 00:04:03,948
Often, we focus on a demo of some kind,

83
00:04:04,408 --> 00:04:06,649
a small slice of the game that establishes our tone

84
00:04:07,029 --> 00:04:08,910
and explores the game's developing mechanics.

85
00:04:10,610 --> 00:04:12,250
Right away, the game starts evolving

86
00:04:12,310 --> 00:04:13,451
because of these initial shoots.

87
00:04:14,179 --> 00:04:18,202
Not only do they help our principal actors start infusing their personality into the characters,

88
00:04:18,682 --> 00:04:23,707
but their choices early on allow the team to adapt to discoveries we've made with the actors on the stage.

89
00:04:24,928 --> 00:04:27,630
For instance, on the very first day of shooting The Last of Us,

90
00:04:28,071 --> 00:04:31,694
we began with a scene where Joel and Ellie are ambushed during their cross-country journey.

91
00:04:32,374 --> 00:04:35,697
Ellie was originally pulled from their pickup truck and pinned helplessly by an enemy,

92
00:04:36,077 --> 00:04:38,780
making her a quasi-damsel in distress for Joel to save.

93
00:04:39,821 --> 00:04:41,602
But Ashley Johnson, who plays Ellie,

94
00:04:42,542 --> 00:04:44,645
had the desire to fight back against her attacker.

95
00:04:45,466 --> 00:04:47,728
So we shot it that way, leading our directors

96
00:04:47,768 --> 00:04:49,731
to go back to design and rethink the character's

97
00:04:49,851 --> 00:04:51,753
overall vulnerability for the rest of the game.

98
00:04:53,135 --> 00:04:55,097
Though we wanted to reinforce the need for the player,

99
00:04:55,317 --> 00:04:57,199
as Joel, to protect Ellie from harm,

100
00:04:57,700 --> 00:04:59,162
it still worked better for her to become

101
00:04:59,262 --> 00:05:01,164
far more capable in combat situations

102
00:05:01,224 --> 00:05:02,365
than we'd originally conceived.

103
00:05:04,517 --> 00:05:07,960
As we continue to shoot, cut scenes are initially our top priority.

104
00:05:08,401 --> 00:05:11,764
Since these are non-interactive beats reserved for the more delicate

105
00:05:11,804 --> 00:05:15,107
and emotional character moments, they require as much animation time

106
00:05:15,147 --> 00:05:17,470
as possible to hit the level of polish required.

107
00:05:19,310 --> 00:05:21,211
We've spoken about our capturing process before,

108
00:05:21,652 --> 00:05:23,894
but there's a couple of things I feel that are essential

109
00:05:23,934 --> 00:05:25,676
to capturing the best performance possible.

110
00:05:26,276 --> 00:05:30,180
Because as an editor, if all I had to start working with

111
00:05:30,220 --> 00:05:31,721
was stale or unnatural material,

112
00:05:32,101 --> 00:05:33,923
there would only be so much we could do in post

113
00:05:34,103 --> 00:05:34,644
to make it better.

114
00:05:36,685 --> 00:05:38,407
A lot goes into how we create scripts

115
00:05:38,767 --> 00:05:40,589
that give actors honest material to play,

116
00:05:40,989 --> 00:05:43,151
but I sadly do not have time to touch on that today.

117
00:05:44,048 --> 00:05:47,531
However, I would like to point out one strength in that process.

118
00:05:48,352 --> 00:05:51,034
Every phase the material goes through is a collaborative effort.

119
00:05:51,834 --> 00:05:55,197
From the start, our creative directors encourage input from the team

120
00:05:55,497 --> 00:05:59,140
and our actors, either before the shoot or during our full-day rehearsals,

121
00:06:00,401 --> 00:06:01,682
especially with our actors.

122
00:06:02,643 --> 00:06:05,485
We even do a table read to break down the script before we rehearse.

123
00:06:06,165 --> 00:06:08,507
If something doesn't feel right, the director and actors

124
00:06:08,547 --> 00:06:10,669
work out what sounds the most natural and try that.

125
00:06:11,550 --> 00:06:15,172
Sometimes when we're shooting, we try a variation over takes

126
00:06:15,452 --> 00:06:17,353
and see what we like best in the edit bay later.

127
00:06:19,494 --> 00:06:21,755
When shooting a scene, we primarily capture it

128
00:06:21,815 --> 00:06:24,437
in one continuous take, unless we need to break it

129
00:06:24,497 --> 00:06:26,918
up for additional set builds or to accommodate a stunt.

130
00:06:27,638 --> 00:06:29,759
Lighting, camera angles, we don't worry about any

131
00:06:29,799 --> 00:06:31,040
of this until post-production.

132
00:06:31,880 --> 00:06:34,321
This lets us focus on getting that perfect master take

133
00:06:34,602 --> 00:06:38,163
with the actors, encouraging the spontaneity improvisation

134
00:06:38,443 --> 00:06:40,745
that brings life and genuine emotion to the scenes.

135
00:06:42,703 --> 00:06:45,885
During the shoots, the creative director acts as the director on set,

136
00:06:46,486 --> 00:06:49,709
partially because that's who's worked most closely with design

137
00:06:49,769 --> 00:06:52,030
throughout the production process, and therefore,

138
00:06:52,371 --> 00:06:54,172
who can give the most context to the actors.

139
00:06:55,313 --> 00:06:57,915
Meanwhile, the editor's job at the shoot is twofold.

140
00:06:58,496 --> 00:07:00,778
First, staying aware of the director's notes,

141
00:07:01,198 --> 00:07:04,100
since then they can later be more helpful at personally executing

142
00:07:04,441 --> 00:07:07,703
or communicating to others the director's intention behind each moment.

143
00:07:09,135 --> 00:07:11,916
And secondly, the editor ensures that we have the material

144
00:07:11,936 --> 00:07:14,136
we need to craft the dialogue performances later.

145
00:07:14,816 --> 00:07:17,197
This includes noting which takes were the best performances

146
00:07:17,257 --> 00:07:20,558
on a particular line, as well as asking for a wild take

147
00:07:20,578 --> 00:07:22,718
to get a clean read of a line when the performance

148
00:07:22,738 --> 00:07:25,339
is still fresh, rather than trying to recreate it

149
00:07:25,379 --> 00:07:26,479
months later in ADR.

150
00:07:27,259 --> 00:07:28,959
This is especially useful for efforts,

151
00:07:29,259 --> 00:07:31,920
those grunts you hear when the players exert themselves,

152
00:07:32,620 --> 00:07:35,341
which often get spoiled by set, prop, or suit noise

153
00:07:35,521 --> 00:07:36,601
while the actors are moving around.

154
00:07:38,309 --> 00:07:39,089
Drake exertion.

155
00:07:39,510 --> 00:07:40,250
Very good.

156
00:07:40,270 --> 00:07:40,450
Marker.

157
00:07:40,810 --> 00:07:41,390
Marker.

158
00:07:41,971 --> 00:07:42,291
Great.

159
00:07:42,311 --> 00:07:44,692
Alright, just give me a hand with this.

160
00:07:44,712 --> 00:07:48,714
Come on, give me a hand with this.

161
00:08:05,381 --> 00:08:08,002
It's some of the most ridiculous things when we have them do well.

162
00:08:10,989 --> 00:08:14,531
Once the footage of our actors is in the can, the real work begins,

163
00:08:15,051 --> 00:08:18,313
breaking it into pieces for the design, animation, and audio teams.

164
00:08:19,073 --> 00:08:22,496
Back at the office, the editor, lead animator, and creative director

165
00:08:22,596 --> 00:08:24,117
start editing as soon as possible.

166
00:08:25,638 --> 00:08:27,579
We found that cutting together reference videos

167
00:08:27,839 --> 00:08:30,300
is the fastest and most efficient way to communicate

168
00:08:30,340 --> 00:08:31,781
the eventual shape of a performance.

169
00:08:32,757 --> 00:08:35,638
After choosing which takes of mocap we want to use,

170
00:08:35,998 --> 00:08:38,238
we create four paneled videos called four ups

171
00:08:38,678 --> 00:08:40,379
that show the reference footage of the actors

172
00:08:40,519 --> 00:08:42,539
alongside intended camera angles.

173
00:08:44,200 --> 00:08:46,820
As we experiment with cameras and massaging the blocking

174
00:08:46,840 --> 00:08:49,541
for the best composition, you end up having to watch them

175
00:08:49,581 --> 00:08:51,961
with a split focus, looking at the face here,

176
00:08:52,181 --> 00:08:53,281
the body and the camera there,

177
00:08:53,682 --> 00:08:55,062
sometimes even listening to audio

178
00:08:55,102 --> 00:08:56,642
that doesn't match up with the actor's lips.

179
00:08:57,973 --> 00:09:00,093
This is because we can take advantage of the fact

180
00:09:00,113 --> 00:09:01,334
that this isn't live action.

181
00:09:01,854 --> 00:09:03,254
We can swap different audio takes

182
00:09:03,294 --> 00:09:04,315
if we need to fix something,

183
00:09:04,615 --> 00:09:07,015
or use those wild takes to cover spoiled dialogue.

184
00:09:07,496 --> 00:09:09,816
The facial motion capture is even ordered separately

185
00:09:10,016 --> 00:09:12,357
after the edit is locked and conformed to match.

186
00:09:12,877 --> 00:09:15,358
So we truly have the freedom to change anything.

187
00:09:16,798 --> 00:09:19,699
Like swapping only one actor's mocap for an alternate take

188
00:09:20,079 --> 00:09:21,540
to get a cool gesture they did in there.

189
00:09:22,424 --> 00:09:24,224
or cutting between two different performances

190
00:09:24,365 --> 00:09:25,485
right in the middle of a shot.

191
00:09:26,226 --> 00:09:28,187
Normally we hide these edits on camera cuts

192
00:09:28,307 --> 00:09:30,408
just like in live action, but if we can't,

193
00:09:30,928 --> 00:09:32,369
our animators then have to clean up

194
00:09:32,389 --> 00:09:33,870
the resulting pop in the mocap.

195
00:09:35,190 --> 00:09:38,852
Or at the most extreme, grabbing the face, audio, and body

196
00:09:39,153 --> 00:09:41,154
all from different sources to cobble together

197
00:09:41,174 --> 00:09:42,174
a moment we don't have.

198
00:09:42,895 --> 00:09:44,696
Usually that's because we discover something,

199
00:09:45,316 --> 00:09:47,017
a way something could play better in the edit,

200
00:09:47,477 --> 00:09:48,918
and since we didn't get it originally,

201
00:09:49,018 --> 00:09:49,858
we've got to fake it.

202
00:09:52,563 --> 00:09:55,807
But usually, the most we do is swap reads of some lines

203
00:09:55,847 --> 00:09:57,348
to increase clarity or subtlety.

204
00:09:57,949 --> 00:09:59,751
There's definitely magic in a performance

205
00:09:59,791 --> 00:10:00,952
that can easily be shattered

206
00:10:01,032 --> 00:10:02,654
if you stray too far from the source.

207
00:10:04,856 --> 00:10:06,117
Once a scene's edit is approved,

208
00:10:06,678 --> 00:10:09,300
that 4UP reference video is funneled to every department

209
00:10:09,320 --> 00:10:11,142
that will be involved in the further translation

210
00:10:11,162 --> 00:10:11,983
of these performances.

211
00:10:12,684 --> 00:10:15,186
This includes animation, props, environment,

212
00:10:15,286 --> 00:10:16,567
lighting, sound, and design.

213
00:10:17,539 --> 00:10:19,542
but they all know the scene isn't picture locked,

214
00:10:20,083 --> 00:10:23,389
more like picture latched, because as I warned,

215
00:10:23,569 --> 00:10:25,453
these edits may very well have to change.

216
00:10:27,436 --> 00:10:28,999
Sometimes a change is required

217
00:10:29,039 --> 00:10:30,081
because of a mistake in the edit.

218
00:10:31,095 --> 00:10:33,497
Nailing the timing of a moment can sometimes be difficult,

219
00:10:33,878 --> 00:10:36,179
since you're essentially looking at mannequins in one pane

220
00:10:36,540 --> 00:10:38,221
and trying to sell an emotional transition

221
00:10:38,241 --> 00:10:39,963
that you can see on an actor in another.

222
00:10:40,743 --> 00:10:42,264
When the facial animation is applied

223
00:10:42,304 --> 00:10:43,706
and we look at the scene full frame,

224
00:10:44,146 --> 00:10:45,927
some things might move just a little too quickly.

225
00:10:46,388 --> 00:10:47,288
So we have to adjust,

226
00:10:47,849 --> 00:10:49,810
and then communicate these timing changes

227
00:10:49,870 --> 00:10:51,071
to all the affected departments.

228
00:10:53,894 --> 00:10:56,716
Another change that comes up is that sets are often altered

229
00:10:56,736 --> 00:10:58,178
to accommodate gameplay revisions.

230
00:10:58,919 --> 00:11:01,041
An entrance or an exit to a space had to move.

231
00:11:01,501 --> 00:11:02,943
There's a wall in front of that camera,

232
00:11:03,443 --> 00:11:05,145
or a cover object sitting right in the middle

233
00:11:05,165 --> 00:11:05,726
of a character.

234
00:11:06,647 --> 00:11:08,909
Usually these require minor animation fixes

235
00:11:09,069 --> 00:11:10,691
like moving characters or cameras,

236
00:11:11,252 --> 00:11:13,214
but at worst, the environment might need

237
00:11:13,234 --> 00:11:14,595
to be reverted by art and design.

238
00:11:18,845 --> 00:11:21,487
The biggest changes that come in maintaining continuity

239
00:11:21,648 --> 00:11:23,849
is in maintaining continuity with gameplay.

240
00:11:24,690 --> 00:11:26,651
Since the transition of characters entering

241
00:11:26,691 --> 00:11:28,513
or leaving a scene needs to feel seamless,

242
00:11:28,853 --> 00:11:30,174
their animations have to match

243
00:11:30,214 --> 00:11:31,735
what's actually happening in gameplay.

244
00:11:32,516 --> 00:11:34,918
Design helps ensure this by creating pinch points

245
00:11:35,118 --> 00:11:37,180
that force a certain action from the player,

246
00:11:37,380 --> 00:11:39,542
like opening a door or vaulting over something,

247
00:11:39,902 --> 00:11:41,463
that will blend into the start of a scene.

248
00:11:42,204 --> 00:11:44,746
And when it's over, we often blend characters' movements

249
00:11:44,846 --> 00:11:47,468
into regular gameplay animations to match on the way out.

250
00:11:51,080 --> 00:11:54,642
But when gameplay changes, so do these entrances and exits.

251
00:11:55,403 --> 00:11:57,905
Often this means recapturing, or at least reanimating,

252
00:11:57,945 --> 00:11:59,046
that portion of the material.

253
00:12:00,247 --> 00:12:01,428
Like this scene in The Last of Us,

254
00:12:02,148 --> 00:12:04,150
which first had to have the camera corrected

255
00:12:04,190 --> 00:12:05,311
to not be behind the player,

256
00:12:05,571 --> 00:12:07,172
because that would be too similar to gameplay.

257
00:12:08,033 --> 00:12:10,374
Then the level changed so that Joel would be in the lead

258
00:12:10,434 --> 00:12:12,456
rather than Ellie, so we needed a pickup

259
00:12:13,797 --> 00:12:15,598
to a new opening where Joel went in first.

260
00:12:20,685 --> 00:12:24,891
As these scenes change, we have to keep careful watch so nothing slips through the cracks.

261
00:12:25,552 --> 00:12:30,138
Sometimes, certain scenes linger in a partially done state for a long time,

262
00:12:30,639 --> 00:12:34,104
waiting on a character model or a set that didn't exist when it was shot, for example.

263
00:12:36,136 --> 00:12:39,199
However, cutscenes are just the tip of the iceberg.

264
00:12:40,039 --> 00:12:41,661
Since we like to keep the player in control

265
00:12:41,701 --> 00:12:44,163
as often as possible, we've increasingly relied

266
00:12:44,203 --> 00:12:45,744
upon methods other than cutscenes

267
00:12:46,005 --> 00:12:47,166
for implementing story beats.

268
00:12:47,866 --> 00:12:50,769
One major way is through animations we call IGCs.

269
00:12:52,734 --> 00:12:54,995
IGC stands for in-game cinematic,

270
00:12:55,556 --> 00:12:56,837
because until Uncharted 4,

271
00:12:57,698 --> 00:12:59,499
all our cut scenes were pre-rendered movies,

272
00:12:59,960 --> 00:13:02,802
so IGCs defined the distinction between animations

273
00:13:02,842 --> 00:13:04,143
that happened live in-game,

274
00:13:04,704 --> 00:13:07,146
versus more traditional non-interactive narrative moments

275
00:13:07,206 --> 00:13:07,826
like cut scenes.

276
00:13:09,508 --> 00:13:11,329
Now that everything plays back in real time,

277
00:13:11,730 --> 00:13:13,671
the biggest distinction is that some aspect

278
00:13:13,691 --> 00:13:15,833
of the animation is usually interactive.

279
00:13:16,574 --> 00:13:18,796
In the very least, the player might have camera control,

280
00:13:19,156 --> 00:13:20,978
but that all depends on the particular IGC.

281
00:13:23,007 --> 00:13:25,008
Some are as insignificant as opening a door

282
00:13:25,248 --> 00:13:27,490
or walking into the frame at the start of a level.

283
00:13:29,290 --> 00:13:31,251
Others are full-blown mini cinematics

284
00:13:31,451 --> 00:13:33,853
sandwiched between gameplay moments with no camera cuts,

285
00:13:34,193 --> 00:13:35,834
like during this puzzle in Uncharted 4.

286
00:13:38,015 --> 00:13:40,636
IGCs are also a clever method we use nowadays

287
00:13:40,696 --> 00:13:42,857
to blend into and out of our cutscenes.

288
00:13:43,518 --> 00:13:45,439
The first or last shot of some cutscenes

289
00:13:45,499 --> 00:13:47,159
on Uncharted 4 were IGCs,

290
00:13:47,640 --> 00:13:49,160
so the camera could blend smoothly,

291
00:13:49,320 --> 00:13:50,701
transitioning on a camera cut

292
00:13:50,861 --> 00:13:52,622
to the rest of the non-interactive cutscene.

293
00:13:57,088 --> 00:13:59,969
There are hundreds of these littered all throughout the game

294
00:14:00,289 --> 00:14:02,850
and they will often change multiple times,

295
00:14:03,370 --> 00:14:05,531
being shortened, lengthened, or recaptured

296
00:14:05,691 --> 00:14:07,331
until design thinks they feel right

297
00:14:07,411 --> 00:14:09,132
within the pace of the gameplay around them.

298
00:14:10,772 --> 00:14:12,533
Editorial, like with cut scenes,

299
00:14:12,813 --> 00:14:14,674
needs to keep up with any timing adjustments,

300
00:14:15,074 --> 00:14:16,494
moving parts of the audio around

301
00:14:16,574 --> 00:14:18,255
to match the animation as it changes.

302
00:14:19,355 --> 00:14:21,476
But even though the interactivity of an IGC

303
00:14:21,636 --> 00:14:23,316
offers great advantages for gameplay,

304
00:14:23,736 --> 00:14:24,797
the way their audio works

305
00:14:24,957 --> 00:14:26,717
sometimes offers additional challenges.

306
00:14:28,800 --> 00:14:31,807
IGC dialogue is similar to a cut scene in that it plays

307
00:14:31,827 --> 00:14:34,072
from the first frame of the animation until the end,

308
00:14:34,794 --> 00:14:36,719
usually containing several lines of dialogue

309
00:14:36,799 --> 00:14:38,864
and or efforts precisely timed to the animation.

310
00:14:40,218 --> 00:14:42,399
However, that is where the similarities end.

311
00:14:43,199 --> 00:14:45,520
Unlike cut scenes, which play back like a movie,

312
00:14:45,700 --> 00:14:47,881
where every volume level or perspective shift

313
00:14:47,941 --> 00:14:49,541
is crafted and controlled,

314
00:14:50,321 --> 00:14:51,822
IGCs often have to account

315
00:14:51,862 --> 00:14:53,462
for a real-time interactive camera.

316
00:14:54,183 --> 00:14:57,584
So IGC dialogue plays directly from the voice box

317
00:14:57,664 --> 00:14:59,324
of each character in 3D space.

318
00:15:00,097 --> 00:15:06,902
This creates different mix issues, because our camera is the listener, i.e. microphone, by default.

319
00:15:07,643 --> 00:15:13,388
The benefit is that the position of the character's voice automatically matches what you're seeing on screen without any post-production work.

320
00:15:14,008 --> 00:15:14,889
Instant realism.

321
00:15:16,650 --> 00:15:24,016
But, the downside is that if the camera is really far away, and you want to hear the speaker clearly, we have to cheat how that line plays.

322
00:15:24,977 --> 00:15:27,179
Or, if the camera cuts while someone is speaking...

323
00:15:27,612 --> 00:15:29,254
Suddenly, the person you hear in your left ear

324
00:15:29,434 --> 00:15:31,056
is now talking on your right mid-word,

325
00:15:31,236 --> 00:15:32,718
which can be extremely distracting.

326
00:15:33,579 --> 00:15:35,060
Like in this moment from Uncharted 2,

327
00:15:35,381 --> 00:15:36,522
we dealt with both problems.

328
00:15:37,063 --> 00:15:39,345
It took a lot of trickery to make Nate's voice audible

329
00:15:39,385 --> 00:15:40,486
from across the ice cave.

330
00:15:41,007 --> 00:15:42,789
But when that camera cuts across the space,

331
00:15:43,189 --> 00:15:45,111
you'll notice we quite couldn't fix the pop

332
00:15:45,292 --> 00:15:46,853
in Nate's voice as the camera cuts.

333
00:16:00,259 --> 00:16:01,180
Switch on your side!

334
00:16:01,680 --> 00:16:02,841
Yeah, yeah.

335
00:16:08,445 --> 00:16:09,886
But wait, there's more.

336
00:16:11,146 --> 00:16:13,448
Cutscenes and IGCs are only half the battle.

337
00:16:14,409 --> 00:16:16,170
Our performances would not feel seamless

338
00:16:16,210 --> 00:16:18,511
without a lot of other systems that play in between them.

339
00:16:19,432 --> 00:16:21,213
But before I break those down further,

340
00:16:21,633 --> 00:16:23,194
I would like to look at an example clip

341
00:16:23,294 --> 00:16:25,416
of what it all looks like when everything comes together.

342
00:16:27,337 --> 00:16:31,421
During this beat of Uncharted 4, Nate and Sam are just starting the next leg of their

343
00:16:31,461 --> 00:16:36,165
journey, exploring the ruins of a Scottish monastery that their rival, Rafe, and the

344
00:16:36,205 --> 00:16:39,388
team of mercenaries he's employed are trying to excavate with dynamite.

345
00:16:40,328 --> 00:16:44,352
The Drake brothers meet the shoreline mercs for the first time, learn the new dynamite

346
00:16:44,372 --> 00:16:49,136
gameplay mechanic, and solve the first puzzle of the level, finding a crate to climb past

347
00:16:49,176 --> 00:16:49,957
a section of ruins.

348
00:16:50,637 --> 00:16:53,220
That is, until another team of mercenaries arrives.

349
00:16:59,933 --> 00:17:00,894
That's a long drop.

350
00:17:02,275 --> 00:17:04,716
Yeah. We need to find another way down.

351
00:17:04,736 --> 00:17:12,160
Hey, this should hold.

352
00:17:12,180 --> 00:17:13,560
Good call.

353
00:17:14,541 --> 00:17:27,768
What the hell is all this?

354
00:17:29,821 --> 00:17:30,762
Excavation equipment.

355
00:17:34,865 --> 00:17:35,426
Shoreline?

356
00:17:36,387 --> 00:17:36,547
What?

357
00:17:37,067 --> 00:17:37,307
Look.

358
00:17:38,749 --> 00:17:40,050
