359
00:18:01,770 --> 00:18:02,090
We're good.

360
00:18:02,110 --> 00:18:03,552
Yeah.

361
00:18:04,413 --> 00:18:05,855
Nice to meet you too, Shoreline.

362
00:18:06,576 --> 00:18:07,877
Seems like they were expecting us.

363
00:18:08,638 --> 00:18:10,701
And like they're searching away from the cathedral.

364
00:18:11,421 --> 00:18:13,584
Which means we should get to that graveyard pronto.

365
00:18:14,005 --> 00:18:14,385
Exactly.

366
00:18:37,893 --> 00:18:38,593
What is this place?

367
00:18:39,033 --> 00:18:40,653
The monks had several living quarters.

368
00:18:40,673 --> 00:18:43,454
The main one being by the graveyard, of course.

369
00:18:44,874 --> 00:18:46,314
Location, location, location.

370
00:18:47,635 --> 00:18:48,695
More shoreline equipment.

371
00:18:49,515 --> 00:18:51,035
At least no shoreline-ers.

372
00:18:56,416 --> 00:18:57,616
Now, what do you bet?

373
00:18:59,877 --> 00:19:00,077
Yep.

374
00:19:01,277 --> 00:19:01,817
Dynamite.

375
00:19:03,558 --> 00:19:04,578
Be careful with that stuff, huh?

376
00:19:13,993 --> 00:19:18,076
I was very loud. Hopefully they didn't hear us.

377
00:19:18,796 --> 00:19:21,018
Hopefully we just blend in with the other explosions.

378
00:19:24,640 --> 00:19:26,621
Look, there's a way up through the roof.

379
00:19:27,582 --> 00:19:30,524
That's too high for a boost though.

380
00:19:30,544 --> 00:19:31,805
Well, let's find something to climb on.

381
00:19:32,745 --> 00:19:32,905
Yeah.

382
00:19:52,935 --> 00:19:55,358
Hey, we can use this to climb out of that building.

383
00:19:55,378 --> 00:20:04,931
There you go. Take that, door.

384
00:20:04,951 --> 00:20:06,894
You're pretty good with that stuff.

385
00:20:07,375 --> 00:20:09,317
Well, I've blown a lot of shit up over the years.

386
00:20:37,739 --> 00:20:38,420
I think we got away.

387
00:20:43,063 --> 00:20:44,944
It's a mellow sequence,

388
00:20:45,524 --> 00:20:47,426
but there's actually a lot going on here.

389
00:20:48,126 --> 00:20:49,767
And every single element that's happening

390
00:20:50,108 --> 00:20:51,549
is helping convey our story beats.

391
00:20:52,689 --> 00:20:54,711
At a glance, these elements include

392
00:20:56,292 --> 00:20:58,474
IGCs when Nate uses his rope

393
00:20:58,774 --> 00:21:00,155
and later when he picks up the dynamite.

394
00:21:01,876 --> 00:21:03,957
Animated gesture layers on Nate and Sam

395
00:21:04,037 --> 00:21:05,258
as they explore and converse.

396
00:21:06,465 --> 00:21:08,687
Oh, and nice.

397
00:21:11,668 --> 00:21:12,129
Still going?

398
00:21:12,229 --> 00:21:14,410
Yes. Animated gesture layers.

399
00:21:16,691 --> 00:21:16,972
Come on.

400
00:21:20,594 --> 00:21:23,956
A, yes. A brief cut scene of Nate

401
00:21:23,976 --> 00:21:26,938
and Sam finding the Shoreline equipment before they're ambushed.

402
00:21:28,759 --> 00:21:31,500
Systemic enemy dialogue from our Shoreline mercenaries

403
00:21:31,660 --> 00:21:32,521
as they attack the player.

404
00:21:34,199 --> 00:21:36,201
Systemic buddy dialogue from Sam

405
00:21:36,261 --> 00:21:38,403
when the player successfully stays in cover.

406
00:21:39,865 --> 00:21:41,907
Efforts as Nate knocks out the last Merc

407
00:21:42,227 --> 00:21:44,310
and then lands from a long drop near those ruins.

408
00:21:45,531 --> 00:21:48,134
And of course, before and after all of this,

409
00:21:48,194 --> 00:21:50,597
there is also crap tons of story dialogue playing.

410
00:21:52,339 --> 00:21:54,201
So, about that story dialogue.

411
00:21:55,478 --> 00:21:57,259
Most of the dialogue you hear in our games

412
00:21:57,539 --> 00:22:01,002
are individual lines scripted by hand with specific timing.

413
00:22:01,782 --> 00:22:04,844
We even have a designer and a scripter 100% dedicated

414
00:22:04,884 --> 00:22:06,445
to creating systems for hooking it up.

415
00:22:07,446 --> 00:22:09,787
They can't complete an entire game on their own

416
00:22:09,908 --> 00:22:11,389
since by the time the game is finished,

417
00:22:11,769 --> 00:22:13,770
there's too much material for them to cover alone,

418
00:22:14,451 --> 00:22:16,512
but they are usually the ones triggering lines

419
00:22:17,092 --> 00:22:19,014
that play based on numerous conditions.

420
00:22:19,594 --> 00:22:21,135
Some as simple as when a player walks

421
00:22:21,155 --> 00:22:23,957
through a defined region, others much more complex.

422
00:22:25,175 --> 00:22:28,917
Rather than play with rigid timing, like cut scenes in IGCs,

423
00:22:29,518 --> 00:22:32,159
we cut our dialogue into pieces that can flexibly respond

424
00:22:32,199 --> 00:22:33,080
to the player's actions.

425
00:22:33,820 --> 00:22:36,662
This also means we can adjust the execution more easily

426
00:22:36,822 --> 00:22:38,363
as things change during development.

427
00:22:40,264 --> 00:22:42,446
These in-game dialogue moments actually make up

428
00:22:42,526 --> 00:22:45,248
a larger percentage of narrative beats than our cut scenes.

429
00:22:46,028 --> 00:22:47,929
We feel this type of material is crucial

430
00:22:48,190 --> 00:22:50,551
because it carries the story forward

431
00:22:50,851 --> 00:22:53,133
by keeping the characters alive between those cut scenes.

432
00:22:54,290 --> 00:22:57,052
It can justify practical and gameplay-driven goals

433
00:22:57,112 --> 00:22:58,453
within the context of the narrative.

434
00:22:59,754 --> 00:23:02,836
Likewise, it informs the player of any changes in tension,

435
00:23:03,036 --> 00:23:04,977
like exploration or combat states.

436
00:23:06,378 --> 00:23:08,179
And it's also a vital tool for selling

437
00:23:08,219 --> 00:23:10,620
the realism of the environment in the player's mind

438
00:23:10,820 --> 00:23:12,842
when the characters respond contextually to it.

439
00:23:14,861 --> 00:23:17,123
Unlike the cut scenes in many of the IGCs,

440
00:23:17,583 --> 00:23:20,125
most of this dialogue does not come from the mocap stage.

441
00:23:20,686 --> 00:23:23,228
That's because it primarily requires the character speaking

442
00:23:23,448 --> 00:23:25,130
while the player is in full control.

443
00:23:26,731 --> 00:23:29,213
So, we record the lion's share of this content

444
00:23:29,453 --> 00:23:30,434
at an ADR studio.

445
00:23:31,215 --> 00:23:32,556
The actors are usually paired up

446
00:23:32,616 --> 00:23:35,038
so we profit from their chemistry, just like at mocap.

447
00:23:35,758 --> 00:23:37,980
Also, they wear the same type of microphones

448
00:23:38,180 --> 00:23:41,003
so that the audio quality matches that of the stage.

449
00:23:43,103 --> 00:23:45,805
The scripts for ADR sessions come online rather late,

450
00:23:46,465 --> 00:23:48,026
as the levels they often reflect

451
00:23:48,066 --> 00:23:49,607
are still being locked down by design.

452
00:23:50,768 --> 00:23:52,069
This means that most of the time,

453
00:23:52,129 --> 00:23:53,389
the actors are reading their lines

454
00:23:53,409 --> 00:23:54,710
without any time to prepare.

455
00:23:55,491 --> 00:23:57,352
So we bring a video capture of the level

456
00:23:57,572 --> 00:23:58,672
in its most current state

457
00:23:59,033 --> 00:24:00,894
to give them as much context as possible.

458
00:24:02,454 --> 00:24:03,855
And any time there is a cut scene

459
00:24:03,875 --> 00:24:05,476
that we've already shot and implemented,

460
00:24:05,876 --> 00:24:07,537
we watch those down with the actors too,

461
00:24:08,038 --> 00:24:10,059
to remind them of the character's emotional state

462
00:24:10,099 --> 00:24:10,899
that they need to match

463
00:24:11,219 --> 00:24:12,640
in order to keep the tone consistent.

464
00:24:14,724 --> 00:24:16,304
Because the game is still in flux,

465
00:24:16,645 --> 00:24:19,025
we record a variety of material in anticipation

466
00:24:19,105 --> 00:24:20,586
of ways in which the game might change.

467
00:24:21,726 --> 00:24:24,106
Gameplay conversations make up the bulk of our recording.

468
00:24:24,727 --> 00:24:26,187
But these aren't always straightforward

469
00:24:26,387 --> 00:24:28,307
because sometimes parts of them are optional.

470
00:24:28,948 --> 00:24:31,068
The actors will perform one version of the conversation

471
00:24:31,088 --> 00:24:33,369
all the way through and then pick up the other versions

472
00:24:33,449 --> 00:24:35,149
right away to keep the energy consistent.

473
00:24:36,950 --> 00:24:38,250
Such as in that Scotland clip,

474
00:24:38,730 --> 00:24:40,470
different lines would play out depending on

475
00:24:40,510 --> 00:24:42,471
when the player interacted with that yellow crate.

476
00:24:46,534 --> 00:24:47,395
How do we open this door?

477
00:24:49,379 --> 00:24:51,362
Look, there's a way up through the roof.

478
00:24:52,484 --> 00:24:53,847
It's too high for a boost, though.

479
00:24:55,189 --> 00:24:56,452
Hey, we can use that yellow crate!

480
00:25:00,606 --> 00:25:03,409
Sometimes we also pick up alternate versions of lines,

481
00:25:03,830 --> 00:25:06,473
alts for short, especially when the level

482
00:25:06,553 --> 00:25:08,996
is in a rougher state and we need to have multiple options

483
00:25:09,116 --> 00:25:10,617
as design locks things down later.

484
00:25:11,558 --> 00:25:13,881
This frequently happens in puzzle spaces among others,

485
00:25:14,502 --> 00:25:17,405
since they require tons of specific VO and animations

486
00:25:17,465 --> 00:25:19,608
to cover what the player does and in what order.

487
00:25:20,934 --> 00:25:24,139
On Uncharted 4, we even kept a wish list of alt lines

488
00:25:24,199 --> 00:25:25,581
that design thought they might need

489
00:25:26,122 --> 00:25:27,624
and tried to cover them all as pickups

490
00:25:27,664 --> 00:25:28,525
near the end of recording.

491
00:25:29,226 --> 00:25:31,710
This resulted in much better coverage for the final game

492
00:25:31,870 --> 00:25:32,951
than we've ever had before.

493
00:25:35,623 --> 00:25:39,106
We also have a whole category we call CYA lines,

494
00:25:39,566 --> 00:25:42,609
as in cover your ass, which are generic phrases like,

495
00:25:42,769 --> 00:25:45,692
hey, look at this, and come on, this way,

496
00:25:46,152 --> 00:25:49,355
which we record in multiple emotional states and contexts

497
00:25:49,675 --> 00:25:51,757
just in case we need them at a later date,

498
00:25:52,277 --> 00:25:53,698
either to help with gameplay changes

499
00:25:54,079 --> 00:25:55,520
or maybe to sell a character beat.

500
00:25:56,100 --> 00:25:58,643
We record these with our heroes and all their buddy allies.

501
00:26:00,753 --> 00:26:04,694
Just like in MoCap, our actors are also encouraged to improvise during ADR.

502
00:26:05,474 --> 00:26:10,216
Sometimes this will inspire us to rewrite and re-record a new version of a conversation

503
00:26:10,336 --> 00:26:10,816
on the spot.

504
00:26:11,976 --> 00:26:16,617
And at the end of most sessions, we also record wild passes of our levels, where the actors

505
00:26:16,677 --> 00:26:19,998
watch the playthrough video again and are encouraged to riff on top of it.

506
00:26:21,017 --> 00:26:23,217
Though our writers try to cover everything we need

507
00:26:23,277 --> 00:26:24,518
in a given section of the game,

508
00:26:24,978 --> 00:26:27,038
this often provides alternate versions of lines

509
00:26:27,338 --> 00:26:29,139
or even completely new conversations

510
00:26:29,459 --> 00:26:31,499
that add enormous amounts of spark and character.

511
00:26:32,240 --> 00:26:34,560
We extract these gems and use them whenever possible.

512
00:26:35,320 --> 00:26:38,401
For instance, Sam's location, location, location line

513
00:26:38,461 --> 00:26:41,362
in the Scotland clip was an improv that Troy Baker threw in,

514
00:26:41,682 --> 00:26:42,162
and we kept it.

515
00:26:44,651 --> 00:26:48,935
All recorded dialogue is then brought back to the office and stacked in time to the video.

516
00:26:49,576 --> 00:26:55,321
This means we each take of line, this means each take of a line is edited in a Pro Tools

517
00:26:55,361 --> 00:26:59,365
playlist and arranged in columns so we can quickly listen down to all the takes of a

518
00:26:59,405 --> 00:27:00,826
line when making our selects.

519
00:27:10,227 --> 00:27:13,169
These picked lines are then edited into individual files

520
00:27:13,209 --> 00:27:16,731
with unique names and uploaded into our dialogue database tool.

521
00:27:17,652 --> 00:27:20,854
Editors also distribute scripts from the database to our designers

522
00:27:21,214 --> 00:27:23,476
so they have a list of what content they need to implement.

523
00:27:25,197 --> 00:27:28,699
Along with the scripts, we also supply another form of reference movie.

524
00:27:29,380 --> 00:27:32,562
Unlike our cut scene 4-ups, which are tied to motion capture data,

525
00:27:33,082 --> 00:27:36,224
these are instead exports of the very movies the actors ADR'd to,

526
00:27:36,604 --> 00:27:39,946
with dialogue placed to match the timing of the actor's original deliveries.

527
00:27:42,807 --> 00:27:43,507
Hang in there, Joel.

528
00:27:43,527 --> 00:27:54,675
Oh, shit.

529
00:27:56,237 --> 00:27:56,457
Okay.

530
00:27:57,477 --> 00:27:58,438
There's got to be another way.

531
00:28:01,801 --> 00:28:06,444
These ref vids help show where and when the individual lines of dialogue should be scripted

532
00:28:06,484 --> 00:28:10,907
to play, so that it feels and sounds like a realistic performance.

533
00:28:11,723 --> 00:28:17,988
Designers use it as a guideline as they translate all this cinematic pacing and subtlety into pretty much scripted math

534
00:28:20,110 --> 00:28:24,614
The goal is to include proper beats for a breath or a natural pause between lines

535
00:28:25,294 --> 00:28:30,158
Either for the speaker to have a new thought or for the companion character to actually listen before responding

536
00:28:30,919 --> 00:28:34,962
When we don't hit this the moment can feel rushed disjointed or flat-out confusing

537
00:28:36,492 --> 00:28:37,953
It sometimes takes several passes

538
00:28:37,993 --> 00:28:39,993
to get the timing right in game.

539
00:28:40,794 --> 00:28:43,074
Designers can only use these movies as a guideline

540
00:28:43,474 --> 00:28:46,355
because often the video's timing was too fast or too slow

541
00:28:46,675 --> 00:28:48,516
and is not completely representative

542
00:28:48,616 --> 00:28:50,437
about how everyone might play the game.

543
00:28:51,417 --> 00:28:53,037
They use their best judgment trying

544
00:28:53,077 --> 00:28:55,358
to keep three different potential play styles in mind.

545
00:28:56,979 --> 00:28:59,840
Some players like to explore, taking their time,

546
00:28:59,980 --> 00:29:02,720
stopping to hear every lovingly crafted line

547
00:29:02,761 --> 00:29:03,721
so they don't miss a thing.

548
00:29:04,657 --> 00:29:07,358
But if we were to time out everything to that play style,

549
00:29:07,678 --> 00:29:09,719
it would ruin the experience of more average players

550
00:29:09,979 --> 00:29:12,260
who like to enjoy the story but keep things moving.

551
00:29:13,620 --> 00:29:15,521
Where we can, the simplest solution

552
00:29:15,801 --> 00:29:17,402
is just to have certain lines not play

553
00:29:17,442 --> 00:29:18,722
if the player is going too fast.

554
00:29:19,202 --> 00:29:20,463
Like in these Scotland ruins,

555
00:29:20,863 --> 00:29:22,104
the line specifically pointing out

556
00:29:22,124 --> 00:29:23,864
that a ledge is too high for a boost

557
00:29:24,184 --> 00:29:26,585
doesn't play if the player rushes out of there

558
00:29:26,645 --> 00:29:28,586
before the previous conversation is finished.

559
00:29:29,647 --> 00:29:30,487
Hey, got the door open.

560
00:29:31,027 --> 00:29:33,468
That was very loud.

561
00:29:34,272 --> 00:29:35,212
Hopefully they didn't hear us.

562
00:29:35,893 --> 00:29:38,113
Hopefully we just blend in with the other explosions.

563
00:29:38,513 --> 00:29:40,493
Look, there's a way up through the roof.

564
00:29:42,534 --> 00:29:43,894
Oh, let's find something to climb on.

565
00:29:44,794 --> 00:29:45,014
Yeah.

566
00:29:46,875 --> 00:29:48,395
And then there's the speedy players

567
00:29:48,695 --> 00:29:49,775
who dash through the puzzles

568
00:29:49,815 --> 00:29:51,176
to get to the next combat setup.

569
00:29:52,136 --> 00:29:54,656
We do our best to get our conversations playing naturally,

570
00:29:54,776 --> 00:29:56,557
but quickly, so they don't get lost,

571
00:29:56,897 --> 00:29:58,297
but sometimes it can't be helped.

572
00:30:01,633 --> 00:30:03,794
Once in a while, we have an area too small

573
00:30:03,834 --> 00:30:05,415
for the amount of VO that has to play

574
00:30:05,815 --> 00:30:07,756
and end up shipping with moments that can feel

575
00:30:07,817 --> 00:30:09,477
like a string of lines back to back,

576
00:30:09,778 --> 00:30:11,619
depending on how quickly the player is going.

577
00:30:12,539 --> 00:30:13,980
Like this moment in Uncharted 3

578
00:30:14,060 --> 00:30:15,981
that just ended up a little too tight

579
00:30:16,201 --> 00:30:18,243
compared to the pacing of the cut scene that preceded it.

580
00:30:21,725 --> 00:30:25,747
Well, who are we to argue with Sir Francis?

581
00:30:27,848 --> 00:30:30,030
When you say we head down there and end this thing.

582
00:30:32,143 --> 00:30:32,903
Once and for all.

583
00:30:40,104 --> 00:30:40,765
Look at this place.

584
00:30:40,785 --> 00:30:42,545
The whole city's resting on this cavern.

585
00:30:42,925 --> 00:30:44,065
Doesn't look very safe, does it?

586
00:30:44,645 --> 00:30:45,626
That's an understatement.

587
00:30:46,186 --> 00:30:47,226
We've got to find a way down there.

588
00:30:52,587 --> 00:30:53,707
If we get the timing right,

589
00:30:54,407 --> 00:30:59,708
it can convey subtlety without needing a specific body gesture or facial performance to sell a moment.

590
00:31:00,574 --> 00:31:01,974
Like in this bit from The Last of Us,

591
00:31:02,394 --> 00:31:05,575
the pause before Ellie's oh line conveys a turn,

592
00:31:06,075 --> 00:31:08,116
her realization about Joel's darker past.

593
00:31:09,136 --> 00:31:10,736
Her follow-up question then gives Joel

594
00:31:10,776 --> 00:31:11,977
an awkward pause of his own.

595
00:31:12,897 --> 00:31:14,537
All of this emotional content managed

596
00:31:14,557 --> 00:31:16,157
to fit in one small stairwell,

597
00:31:16,417 --> 00:31:17,738
even if the player never stops.

598
00:31:19,478 --> 00:31:20,458
Come on, let's get out of here.

599
00:31:22,599 --> 00:31:28,300
How did you know?

600
00:31:28,320 --> 00:31:29,560
Know what?

601
00:31:30,153 --> 00:31:30,913
What about the ambush?

602
00:31:32,113 --> 00:31:33,153
I've been on both sides.

603
00:31:34,974 --> 00:31:35,114
Oh.

604
00:31:38,894 --> 00:31:39,635
So, uh,

605
00:31:40,215 --> 00:31:41,355
you kill a lot of innocent people?

606
00:31:41,375 --> 00:31:45,496
Yeah.

607
00:31:45,536 --> 00:31:46,456
We'll take that as a yes.

608
00:31:47,316 --> 00:31:48,316
Take it however you want.

609
00:31:52,537 --> 00:31:55,117
That moment worked on dialogue timing alone.

610
00:31:55,918 --> 00:31:56,818
But when we need more...

611
00:31:57,333 --> 00:32:01,280
we now can dynamically add extra body motions to our story dialogue

612
00:32:01,320 --> 00:32:03,604
to increase physical and emotional realism.

613
00:32:04,505 --> 00:32:07,129
In that Scotland clip, when you saw Nate waving his arm

614
00:32:07,170 --> 00:32:09,113
and actually looking at Sam while talking to him,

615
00:32:09,594 --> 00:32:11,577
that was an example of our gesture system.

616
00:32:13,268 --> 00:32:16,371
In previous games, we've had all sorts of contextual move sets

617
00:32:16,511 --> 00:32:19,293
and animation that helped sell the reality of the hero's

618
00:32:19,333 --> 00:32:21,955
world by having him or her react to their environment,

619
00:32:22,695 --> 00:32:24,256
whether it be recoiling from fire,

620
00:32:24,697 --> 00:32:26,798
stumbling while exhausted, bracing themselves

621
00:32:26,838 --> 00:32:28,199
against walls, et cetera.

622
00:32:29,880 --> 00:32:31,501
Our designers are also able to play

623
00:32:31,562 --> 00:32:34,584
additional unique animations on our AI characters

624
00:32:34,624 --> 00:32:36,405
to help bring them to life contextually.

625
00:32:36,825 --> 00:32:39,547
That's what allows Sam to look around and dynamically check

626
00:32:39,587 --> 00:32:40,388
out the world around him.

627
00:32:42,780 --> 00:32:46,080
But now we employ an additional level of detail, gestures.

628
00:32:46,880 --> 00:32:48,981
These are partial animations that play on top

629
00:32:49,021 --> 00:32:51,381
of normal gameplay animations, like a head shake,

630
00:32:51,441 --> 00:32:53,282
an arm pointing, a shrug, et cetera.

631
00:32:53,902 --> 00:32:55,942
The player can be running, climbing, or crouching,

632
00:32:56,002 --> 00:32:57,683
and these layers will usually still play.

633
00:32:58,803 --> 00:33:00,443
In case you're wondering why sometimes an arm

634
00:33:00,503 --> 00:33:01,503
isn't moving in that clip,

635
00:33:01,903 --> 00:33:03,964
that's because it's not part of the animation's layer,

636
00:33:04,544 --> 00:33:06,964
meaning the player can be carrying a gun or another object

637
00:33:06,984 --> 00:33:08,885
while the rest of the body does the gesture.

638
00:33:11,693 --> 00:33:17,058
One of the ways we sell these moments is by hooking up a specific gesture to a line of dialogue in script.

639
00:33:17,999 --> 00:33:22,143
So when each line plays, the gestures play on top of whatever the character is doing.

640
00:33:22,984 --> 00:33:28,469
Programming and scripting magic also helps the speaking characters actually look at each other dynamically when appropriate.

641
00:33:30,512 --> 00:33:33,012
Since we don't record specific gestures for every line,

642
00:33:33,372 --> 00:33:36,273
the final performance isn't as rich as a cut scene might be,

643
00:33:36,813 --> 00:33:38,954
but the result is still an added level of life

644
00:33:39,034 --> 00:33:40,695
that doesn't restrict the player's movement

645
00:33:40,995 --> 00:33:42,235
as they roam around the game world.

646
00:33:43,975 --> 00:33:47,116
Though we can also hook up custom facial animation gestures

647
00:33:47,236 --> 00:33:48,417
to lines in the same way,

648
00:33:48,797 --> 00:33:50,357
we usually don't go to the extra work,

649
00:33:50,857 --> 00:33:51,998
since the camera is normally

650
00:33:52,038 --> 00:33:53,398
behind the player character's head

651
00:33:53,718 --> 00:33:55,999
and far enough away from all other speaking characters.

652
00:33:57,050 --> 00:33:59,751
By default, we employ a neat procedural system,

653
00:34:00,031 --> 00:34:02,212
which generates lip sync and facial animations

654
00:34:02,532 --> 00:34:05,093
using the audio file's amplitude and subtitle text.

655
00:34:06,253 --> 00:34:08,914
This place, monks had several living quarters.

656
00:34:09,695 --> 00:34:11,696
Main one being by the graveyard, of course.

657
00:34:13,096 --> 00:34:14,517
Location, location, location.

658
00:34:18,418 --> 00:34:19,839
Besides the story dialogue,

659
00:34:20,279 --> 00:34:22,880
we have another category of lines called systemic VO.

660
00:34:23,746 --> 00:34:26,047
These groups of lines, or these are groups of lines

661
00:34:26,247 --> 00:34:28,248
with similar context that can play

662
00:34:28,288 --> 00:34:30,069
when triggered by AI-driven events.

663
00:34:30,890 --> 00:34:32,471
This material helps to add life,

664
00:34:32,971 --> 00:34:34,452
reinforce character relationships,

665
00:34:34,792 --> 00:34:36,713
and provide feedback in various situations

666
00:34:36,753 --> 00:34:37,473
throughout the game,

667
00:34:38,054 --> 00:34:39,995
mostly during types of gameplay scenarios

668
00:34:40,055 --> 00:34:42,176
that use repeated systems like combat.

669
00:34:44,297 --> 00:34:46,018
When an enemy spots the player, for instance,

670
00:34:46,278 --> 00:34:48,460
they have specific lines that they use to call that out.

671
00:34:48,920 --> 00:34:50,501
There he is, I see him.

672
00:34:51,101 --> 00:34:52,683
These buckets, as we call them,

673
00:34:53,023 --> 00:34:55,024
offer multiple varieties that can play

674
00:34:55,084 --> 00:34:56,405
based on the same situation,

675
00:34:56,725 --> 00:34:57,906
so the player doesn't just hear,

676
00:34:58,106 --> 00:35:00,388
I see them, over and over and over.

677
00:35:01,429 --> 00:35:02,670
At the end of our Scotland demo,

678
00:35:03,010 --> 00:35:04,891
Sam called out one of his systemic lines

679
00:35:05,111 --> 00:35:07,393
to indicate the player is still hidden from the enemy.

680
00:35:07,853 --> 00:35:09,895
The entire bucket consists of these lines.

681
00:35:11,376 --> 00:35:12,557
I think we got away.

682
00:35:13,831 --> 00:35:15,092
Hurry, Nathan, we lost them.

683
00:35:17,113 --> 00:35:17,653
We lost them.

684
00:35:18,253 --> 00:35:19,334
I think we lost them.

685
00:35:20,795 --> 00:35:22,095
I think they lost track of us.

686
00:35:23,156 --> 00:35:24,617
Looks like we gave them the slip.

687
00:35:29,599 --> 00:35:32,341
This sort of dialogue serves a practical function in terms

688
00:35:32,401 --> 00:35:35,343
of player feedback, but it also keeps the characters alive

689
00:35:35,403 --> 00:35:38,444
and reacting to what's going on in the same way the storylines do,

690
00:35:39,525 --> 00:35:42,306
which is why we don't only use systemic dialogue for our enemies.

691
00:35:43,402 --> 00:35:46,105
Any dialogue triggered by AI, rather than just script,

692
00:35:46,265 --> 00:35:47,386
falls into this category,

693
00:35:47,806 --> 00:35:49,588
including buckets for any major characters,

694
00:35:49,868 --> 00:35:52,150
the hero, their AI-controlled buddies,

695
00:35:53,171 --> 00:35:55,192
and, of course, all our multiplayer characters,

696
00:35:55,333 --> 00:35:57,795
since that mode is pretty much all combat mechanics.

697
00:35:59,997 --> 00:36:02,479
The system is controlled by the global tension state,

698
00:36:02,819 --> 00:36:04,521
which we break down into four stages,

699
00:36:05,081 --> 00:36:08,424
unaware, investigate, search, and combat.

700
00:36:10,571 --> 00:36:13,592
In Unaware, any threats nearby have no knowledge

701
00:36:13,612 --> 00:36:15,173
of the player or their companions.

702
00:36:15,853 --> 00:36:18,454
Enemies can converse with custom story-based dialogue,

703
00:36:18,554 --> 00:36:20,535
like they did at the very end of that Scotland clip.

704
00:36:21,356 --> 00:36:22,756
The player and his buddies, meanwhile,

705
00:36:23,036 --> 00:36:24,917
will likely be in standard explore mode.

706
00:36:25,517 --> 00:36:27,298
This is the natural state of the game.

707
00:36:28,078 --> 00:36:29,819
If they get close to enemies in this state,

708
00:36:30,259 --> 00:36:32,100
buddies and the hero will use whispered versions

709
00:36:32,140 --> 00:36:34,161
of their various buckets, so the characters sound

710
00:36:34,181 --> 00:36:35,262
like they're trying to stay hidden.

711
00:36:37,146 --> 00:36:39,448
In Investigate, tension rises a bit.

712
00:36:39,968 --> 00:36:41,650
The enemies heard or saw some evidence

713
00:36:41,690 --> 00:36:42,631
of player interference.

714
00:36:43,591 --> 00:36:45,973
Then they try to uncover the source of the distraction,

715
00:36:46,294 --> 00:36:47,835
now playing their systemic buckets

716
00:36:48,035 --> 00:36:48,976
regarding what they saw,

717
00:36:49,236 --> 00:36:51,738
checking in if anyone saw anything, et cetera.

718
00:36:52,459 --> 00:36:53,840
This is the first level of tension

719
00:36:53,900 --> 00:36:55,261
where the player would feel threatened

720
00:36:55,662 --> 00:36:56,642
and that they should either fight

721
00:36:56,903 --> 00:36:57,803
or get the hell out of there.

722
00:36:59,809 --> 00:37:02,131
In Search, tension is near its breaking point

723
00:37:02,371 --> 00:37:04,793
because enemies saw the player, then lost track of them.

724
00:37:05,393 --> 00:37:07,555
They speak buckets of lines so the player can audibly

725
00:37:07,615 --> 00:37:10,357
locate the enemies attempting to converge on their position.

726
00:37:11,157 --> 00:37:12,899
Feedback from the heroes remains whispered,

727
00:37:13,179 --> 00:37:15,400
including buddies pointing out where the nearest enemy is.

728
00:37:16,081 --> 00:37:17,482
On your left, behind you.

729
00:37:18,162 --> 00:37:19,684
Or warning them if someone approaching

730
00:37:19,784 --> 00:37:20,944
is carrying a powerful weapon.

731
00:37:21,545 --> 00:37:22,666
Look out, shotgun.

732
00:37:23,226 --> 00:37:23,767
That sort of thing.

733
00:37:25,678 --> 00:37:27,820
Combat is when all hell breaks loose,

734
00:37:28,240 --> 00:37:31,302
and in our games uses almost exclusively systemic dialogue.

735
00:37:32,322 --> 00:37:34,543
But since we want it to feel as nuanced

736
00:37:34,623 --> 00:37:36,224
as any of the quieter story moments,

737
00:37:36,544 --> 00:37:38,445
we employ a lot of buckets to cover

738
00:37:38,485 --> 00:37:40,126
a variety of potential situations.

739
00:37:42,067 --> 00:37:43,348
Enemies are aware of the player

740
00:37:43,708 --> 00:37:45,909
and actively trying to attack him or her

741
00:37:45,929 --> 00:37:48,211
with guns, fists, or whatever other means they have.

742
00:37:48,882 --> 00:37:50,663
They have lines announcing when they are flanking,

743
00:37:50,924 --> 00:37:52,705
pointing out the player's exact location,

744
00:37:53,326 --> 00:37:55,288
or warning each other the player has a power weapon

745
00:37:55,308 --> 00:37:57,029
like an RPG or a Molotov cocktail.

746
00:37:58,571 --> 00:38:00,353
Buddies continue to warn the player

747
00:38:00,393 --> 00:38:01,554
the same as they do in stealth,

748
00:38:01,934 --> 00:38:03,015
but instead of whispering,

749
00:38:03,315 --> 00:38:05,277
their lines are now shouted over gunfire.

750
00:38:06,192 --> 00:38:08,175
We also have dialogue that helps emphasize

751
00:38:08,215 --> 00:38:09,617
their relationship to the hero,

752
00:38:10,057 --> 00:38:11,199
i.e. that they care about them.

753
00:38:11,880 --> 00:38:14,443
Buddies ask if the hero is okay after they've been shot

754
00:38:14,503 --> 00:38:15,745
or stumbled by an explosion.

755
00:38:16,245 --> 00:38:18,048
They shout out that they're coming to rescue the player

756
00:38:18,088 --> 00:38:19,169
if they're grabbed by an enemy,

757
00:38:19,630 --> 00:38:20,972
and say thank you to the player

758
00:38:21,112 --> 00:38:22,233
if they are rescued in return.

759
00:38:24,330 --> 00:38:26,591
The hero also has dialogue to connect the player

760
00:38:26,631 --> 00:38:27,692
to their emotional state,

761
00:38:27,992 --> 00:38:30,034
like the stress of diving out of the way of a grenade

762
00:38:30,054 --> 00:38:31,234
would be, oh God,

763
00:38:31,775 --> 00:38:34,297
or stealing themselves up while reloading in cover.

764
00:38:34,837 --> 00:38:37,619
Drake's is usually like, okay, here we go.

765
00:38:38,940 --> 00:38:40,281
There's usually something that plays

766
00:38:40,321 --> 00:38:42,022
after taking down an enemy as well.

767
00:38:42,462 --> 00:38:44,163
In Uncharted, it's usually a funny quip

768
00:38:44,203 --> 00:38:46,105
that suits the tone like, lights out,

769
00:38:46,645 --> 00:38:48,026
whereas in The Last of Us,

770
00:38:48,106 --> 00:38:51,628
it matched the world's grittier tone, just, okay.

771
00:38:54,383 --> 00:38:56,764
Since systemic lines have a more functional purpose,

772
00:38:57,065 --> 00:38:59,466
they sometimes lack the subtlety or subtext

773
00:38:59,546 --> 00:39:01,047
that our longer conversations do.

774
00:39:01,868 --> 00:39:03,929
But they always maintain the same personality

775
00:39:04,029 --> 00:39:05,170
as the character delivering them,

776
00:39:05,550 --> 00:39:07,151
so that the player doesn't become weary

777
00:39:07,191 --> 00:39:08,492
of hearing the exact same thing

778
00:39:08,572 --> 00:39:10,313
from multiple characters over and over.

779
00:39:11,597 --> 00:39:14,219
For example, Sam calls our main character Nathan,

780
00:39:14,359 --> 00:39:16,381
or little brother in a lot of his systemic warnings,

781
00:39:16,621 --> 00:39:18,403
and is more ball-busting in his tone,

782
00:39:18,983 --> 00:39:20,104
while Sully calls him kid

783
00:39:20,125 --> 00:39:21,526
and maintains a more paternal tone.

784
00:39:22,226 --> 00:39:25,510
Elena calls him Nate and has her own brand

785
00:39:25,590 --> 00:39:27,651
of loving exasperation with our hero

786
00:39:28,032 --> 00:39:28,933
in her pattern of speech.

787
00:39:31,249 --> 00:39:32,810
Even with personality thrown in though,

788
00:39:33,170 --> 00:39:35,332
these lines could still sound somewhat repetitive.

789
00:39:36,012 --> 00:39:37,394
So we have a shuffle system,

790
00:39:37,654 --> 00:39:40,816
which keeps track of every line said by every AI group,

791
00:39:41,217 --> 00:39:43,739
advancing the cue for any one bucket across the board

792
00:39:43,779 --> 00:39:46,441
when they speak, ensuring the same exact line

793
00:39:46,481 --> 00:39:47,582
will not be heard frequently.

794
00:39:48,463 --> 00:39:51,185
If enemies spot the player, one might yell, I see him.

795
00:39:51,885 --> 00:39:54,327
The next time that happens, rather than hear, I see him,

796
00:39:54,507 --> 00:39:56,229
again, the player will hear, it's him,

797
00:39:56,489 --> 00:39:57,430
or some other variant.

798
00:39:58,275 --> 00:40:02,556
Not until the bucket has been exhausted by the shovel system does it reset to the top again.

799
00:40:03,156 --> 00:40:09,017
We try to record 10 to 20 different lines per category that might be heard the most to avoid

800
00:40:09,037 --> 00:40:15,279
the player hearing the repetition in any one play session. Sometimes the lines are also written to

801
00:40:15,319 --> 00:40:20,720
be modular so they can be stitched together based on a situation. Not only does this allow for a

802
00:40:20,760 --> 00:40:24,901
variety in the simulation, but it makes the enemies seem alive and intelligent.

803
00:40:26,339 --> 00:40:28,180
In The Last of Us, an enemy might say,

804
00:40:28,440 --> 00:40:30,661
hey, you two, go search over there.

805
00:40:31,582 --> 00:40:33,442
Each of these is a separate bucket of lines

806
00:40:33,482 --> 00:40:36,324
that plays back to back, utilizing natural pauses

807
00:40:36,364 --> 00:40:38,405
to make them sound like complete, varied thoughts.

808
00:40:39,045 --> 00:40:41,286
In another scenario, it might play as,

809
00:40:41,386 --> 00:40:44,688
hey, you, go check the alley, or some other variant.

810
00:40:47,054 --> 00:40:49,197
One subtle way we keep things feeling more real

811
00:40:49,557 --> 00:40:51,961
is by avoiding repetition, not just in lines,

812
00:40:52,081 --> 00:40:53,402
but in the voices themselves.

813
00:40:54,183 --> 00:40:56,747
Since we have a limited number of actors voicing our NPCs,

814
00:40:57,247 --> 00:40:59,050
we try to make sure they have different voice types,

815
00:40:59,310 --> 00:41:00,792
medium, low, et cetera,

816
00:41:01,253 --> 00:41:02,735
so that the player won't hear voices

817
00:41:02,775 --> 00:41:04,257
that sound the same over and over.

818
00:41:05,195 --> 00:41:10,099
Also, as I mentioned, enemies are often initially encountered while they're having a story conversation,

819
00:41:10,400 --> 00:41:12,462
customized to that particular group or area.

820
00:41:13,082 --> 00:41:17,446
We try to keep track of which actor's voice is being used in each conversation, then try

821
00:41:17,486 --> 00:41:21,570
our best to not use that actor in the next setup, further avoiding repetition.

822
00:41:23,650 --> 00:41:27,371
A tricky situation that then comes up with these enemy conversations is how to interrupt

823
00:41:27,532 --> 00:41:28,912
these lines that are already playing.

824
00:41:29,673 --> 00:41:33,814
If the player shows up in their vision cones, they have to switch to their systemic dialogue

825
00:41:33,874 --> 00:41:34,735
and go into combat.

826
00:41:35,595 --> 00:41:39,837
So we cut off a line, wait a split second, and then just play the systemic dialogue as

827
00:41:39,897 --> 00:41:42,559
if the enemy had interrupted themselves voluntarily.

828
00:41:49,418 --> 00:41:51,260
Take a breath. Who's dead?

829
00:41:51,280 --> 00:41:54,042
The whole crew. The 76th...

830
00:41:59,087 --> 00:42:03,331
For a long time, this rough method was the only way we had to interrupt conversations.

831
00:42:04,112 --> 00:42:09,537
However, the addition of a drivable vehicle in Uncharted 4, which the player could exit at any time,

832
00:42:10,097 --> 00:42:14,001
meant entire sequences of lines might be skipped because the player wanted to explore a little.

833
00:42:15,773 --> 00:42:18,175
This forced us to come up with a more elegant solution

834
00:42:18,215 --> 00:42:20,716
for interrupting and resuming dialogue between Nate

835
00:42:20,756 --> 00:42:23,218
and his buddies, ensuring conversations couldn't

836
00:42:23,258 --> 00:42:24,638
so easily be lost forever.

837
00:42:25,999 --> 00:42:28,060
We recorded more buckets of lines regarding

838
00:42:28,340 --> 00:42:31,622
and responding to the player stopping the 4x4 and exiting,

839
00:42:31,983 --> 00:42:34,504
then attempting to resume the conversation upon return.

840
00:42:36,445 --> 00:42:38,406
To keep things in line with our story dialogue,

841
00:42:38,806 --> 00:42:40,507
the tone of these interrupts had to be different,

842
00:42:40,928 --> 00:42:41,748
depending on the nature

843
00:42:41,768 --> 00:42:43,249
of the characters' current relationships.

844
00:42:44,144 --> 00:42:49,348
In the plains of Madagascar, Nate is comfortably exploring with Sully and Sam, so his tone is more casual.

845
00:43:10,265 --> 00:43:15,049
Avery was the most wanted man in the world, so if he was hiding something out here, it makes sense he'd need lookouts.

846
00:43:18,511 --> 00:43:25,637
On the Libertalia island, by contrast, Nate and Elena's relationship is strained, so he's more subdued when he hops out of the car.

847
00:43:26,958 --> 00:43:31,241
Well, Rafe is a good match for Shoreline. He needs their muscle and they need his money.

848
00:43:31,622 --> 00:43:33,903
They do? They seem pretty well stocked.

849
00:43:34,424 --> 00:43:36,125
Shoreline got involved in a couple of sub

850
00:43:36,165 --> 00:43:36,525
Hold up.

851
00:43:36,866 --> 00:43:37,946
Wait, what? You see something?

852
00:43:43,577 --> 00:43:44,358
Okay, all done.

853
00:43:44,818 --> 00:43:49,801
Yeah, so Shoreline got involved in a couple of civil wars that didn't come out.

854
00:43:53,564 --> 00:43:58,287
To make it sound natural when the character stops speaking, we had the actors record glottal stops,

855
00:43:58,807 --> 00:44:01,288
the sound that a person's throat makes when it stops speaking.

856
00:44:01,969 --> 00:44:04,951
These would play to cut off the lines in as natural a way as possible.

857
00:44:06,428 --> 00:44:06,568
But...

858
00:44:08,349 --> 00:44:09,550
Uh...

859
00:44:10,792 --> 00:44:10,932
But...

860
00:44:11,792 --> 00:44:11,933
Um...

861
00:44:14,355 --> 00:44:14,795
But...

862
00:44:16,397 --> 00:44:17,117
Solis were the best.

863
00:44:20,180 --> 00:44:22,742
Sometimes, we edited alternate versions of lines

864
00:44:23,043 --> 00:44:25,545
that would flow more properly when coming out of an interruption.

865
00:44:26,125 --> 00:44:28,187
This meant combing through an entire conversation

866
00:44:28,307 --> 00:44:30,069
and marking which lines needed alts

867
00:44:30,229 --> 00:44:32,331
in case the conversation resumed on that line.

868
00:44:33,277 --> 00:44:38,041
In retrospect, we wish we had purposely recorded alternate versions to restart a conversation,

869
00:44:38,282 --> 00:44:39,863
rather than just edit the originals.

870
00:44:40,404 --> 00:44:43,927
This system is still very new, and we are looking forward to building on it more in

871
00:44:43,967 --> 00:44:44,647
future releases.

872
00:44:46,649 --> 00:44:49,912
There's one last category of dialogue to cover briefly, efforts.

873
00:44:50,713 --> 00:44:56,518
Besides during those wild takes we get at MoCap, we record lots and lots and lots of

874
00:44:56,618 --> 00:44:59,160
efforts of various types with each of our actors.

875
00:44:59,940 --> 00:45:01,940
Mostly because they give feedback to the player

876
00:45:02,080 --> 00:45:03,961
while also helping the characters come alive,

877
00:45:04,341 --> 00:45:06,681
selling all those physical situations like climbing,

878
00:45:06,781 --> 00:45:09,602
fighting, and dying that happen in our games.

879
00:45:11,562 --> 00:45:13,463
Just having breathing from the characters alone,

880
00:45:13,843 --> 00:45:15,543
especially in situations that are tense

881
00:45:15,743 --> 00:45:16,603
or when they're fatigued,

882
00:45:17,023 --> 00:45:19,144
also helps give a sense of what a character's feeling

883
00:45:19,244 --> 00:45:20,484
without them having to state it.

884
00:45:22,324 --> 00:45:24,705
When recording, we have actors chase videos

885
00:45:24,745 --> 00:45:26,725
of a player grappling, fighting, and falling,

886
00:45:27,145 --> 00:45:28,966
so they have context for the sounds they're making.

887
00:45:29,856 --> 00:45:32,738
We often get different sizes, small, medium, large,

888
00:45:33,399 --> 00:45:35,621
of each sound and play the appropriate ones based

889
00:45:35,681 --> 00:45:36,962
on the intensity of the animation.

890
00:45:38,783 --> 00:45:42,326
And as most efforts are vocally stressful, we always record them

891
00:45:42,446 --> 00:45:43,387
at the end of a session.

892
00:45:43,928 --> 00:45:46,610
In fact, we do the same with any shouted material,

893
00:45:46,970 --> 00:45:49,252
so we don't blow out an actor's voice in the first hour.

894
00:45:51,634 --> 00:45:54,936
So, as all of these systems and animations

895
00:45:55,036 --> 00:45:57,217
start coming together, that is where the glut

896
00:45:57,297 --> 00:45:59,539
of minor and major changes truly start.

897
00:46:00,339 --> 00:46:02,621
A cut scene or a conversation might work in a vacuum,

898
00:46:03,161 --> 00:46:05,342
but it's not until we get these pieces into the game

899
00:46:05,402 --> 00:46:07,043
that we can truly judge what works.

900
00:46:08,964 --> 00:46:10,805
It's about getting it right on the stick

901
00:46:11,286 --> 00:46:13,907
and feeling it out, and then making sure

902
00:46:13,927 --> 00:46:16,809
the performances remain consistent despite the adjustments.

903
00:46:17,572 --> 00:46:20,354
We continually tweak, swap, and rearrange our dialogue

904
00:46:20,454 --> 00:46:22,756
and animation, sometimes over the course of years,

905
00:46:23,396 --> 00:46:25,097
all to improve the emotional connection

906
00:46:25,357 --> 00:46:27,379
between the player and what's going on around them.

907
00:46:29,140 --> 00:46:31,501
First and foremost, not all the content we write

908
00:46:31,521 --> 00:46:33,803
and record works in the final context of the game.

909
00:46:34,684 --> 00:46:36,925
Even if nothing changed in design or animation,

910
00:46:37,245 --> 00:46:39,207
sometimes an emotional beat just feels false.

911
00:46:39,967 --> 00:46:42,329
If possible, we will alter that VO with an edit.

912
00:46:43,161 --> 00:46:47,322
By adding pauses or stealing a breath, sigh, or laugh from somewhere else and cobbling

913
00:46:47,362 --> 00:46:50,203
it onto the line, it can really make moments sound more natural.

914
00:46:52,083 --> 00:46:55,344
Our systemic dialogue might have similar problems when working in context.

915
00:46:56,144 --> 00:46:59,685
Sometimes an AI bucket will fire in a situation that's tonally inappropriate.

916
00:47:00,565 --> 00:47:03,766
Like Nathan Drake's bucket of quips he might spout off any time he knocks a dude out.

917
00:47:04,683 --> 00:47:07,464
If the tone of the game at that point is more serious,

918
00:47:07,924 --> 00:47:11,105
our designers flag that area to suppress all the jokey VO

919
00:47:11,425 --> 00:47:13,566
until it's appropriate for it to play later in the game.

920
00:47:14,426 --> 00:47:16,607
The same goes for all the buddies systemic dialogue.

921
00:47:18,647 --> 00:47:21,588
Another possibility is that a small or not so small

922
00:47:21,648 --> 00:47:23,349
bit of exposition might need to change.

923
00:47:23,989 --> 00:47:25,489
Sometimes it's contained in a cut scene,

924
00:47:25,950 --> 00:47:27,230
others it's a gameplay line

925
00:47:27,270 --> 00:47:28,911
whose context was altered by design.

926
00:47:29,771 --> 00:47:31,731
Usually something this specific cannot be fixed

927
00:47:31,751 --> 00:47:34,052
with an edit, a new line needs to be recorded.

928
00:47:36,041 --> 00:47:38,603
There are also times when a line is making things confusing,

929
00:47:38,963 --> 00:47:40,164
so it just has to go.

930
00:47:40,964 --> 00:47:42,745
We hold many focus tests to determine

931
00:47:42,766 --> 00:47:45,748
where the pacing drags, augmenting or cutting as needed

932
00:47:45,788 --> 00:47:48,309
to hit the ideal amount of gameplay between story beats.

933
00:47:49,150 --> 00:47:51,912
Since we overwrite our levels anyway,

934
00:47:52,352 --> 00:47:55,194
we can usually afford to cut part or all of an exchange

935
00:47:55,634 --> 00:47:57,175
and move another bit of dialogue in

936
00:47:57,235 --> 00:47:59,016
to fill the hole as necessary.

937
00:48:00,918 --> 00:48:02,939
All these adjustments make the game better,

938
00:48:03,680 --> 00:48:06,182
but we also have limits on what we can change.

939
00:48:06,782 --> 00:48:08,163
As the project draws to a close,

940
00:48:08,383 --> 00:48:10,905
the first hard wall we hit is localization.

941
00:48:12,687 --> 00:48:14,548
Localization, for those that might not know,

942
00:48:15,068 --> 00:48:17,330
is the process of translating and re-recording

943
00:48:17,470 --> 00:48:19,792
all text and dialogue into dozens of language

944
00:48:19,832 --> 00:48:20,853
for international players.

945
00:48:22,079 --> 00:48:26,584
Games at some point have to lock, recording no more new lines and writing no more new

946
00:48:26,624 --> 00:48:31,028
text so that all the existing material can go through this process in time for shipping.

947
00:48:32,510 --> 00:48:36,894
The problem is, nowadays, the deadline for localization is not after the game is finished,

948
00:48:37,435 --> 00:48:38,676
it's at least a few months prior.

949
00:48:39,298 --> 00:48:41,378
which, especially since recorded dialogue

950
00:48:41,438 --> 00:48:43,679
is often so hyper-specific to the actions

951
00:48:43,719 --> 00:48:46,399
happening on screen, leads to a greater problem

952
00:48:46,439 --> 00:48:48,739
when things in the game evolve after that date.

953
00:48:49,360 --> 00:48:51,080
Because once we've reached the LOC deadline,

954
00:48:51,600 --> 00:48:53,140
nothing new can be recorded.

955
00:48:55,181 --> 00:48:57,601
This phase is when those generic CYA lines

956
00:48:57,741 --> 00:48:58,781
become really handy.

957
00:48:59,441 --> 00:49:01,182
We can use them to patch areas of the game

958
00:49:01,202 --> 00:49:02,482
that evolved after the deadline.

959
00:49:03,102 --> 00:49:04,702
Need to direct a player's attention

960
00:49:04,742 --> 00:49:05,722
to a solution to a puzzle?

961
00:49:06,223 --> 00:49:07,243
Hey, look at this.

962
00:49:08,077 --> 00:49:10,061
Does a character shout out, this way, come on,

963
00:49:10,121 --> 00:49:11,865
but you want to sell that the buddy is following?

964
00:49:12,245 --> 00:49:14,189
Add in a right behind you in response.

965
00:49:15,091 --> 00:49:16,955
This type of dialogue has become so essential,

966
00:49:17,095 --> 00:49:19,159
we intend to record even more lines like it

967
00:49:19,279 --> 00:49:20,061
on future projects.

968
00:49:21,783 --> 00:49:24,464
Like Uncharted 4, we didn't know if the kids' escape

969
00:49:24,504 --> 00:49:26,264
and the manor flashback would feel better

970
00:49:26,305 --> 00:49:29,006
as a tense stealth sequence or a balls-to-the-wall chase

971
00:49:29,026 --> 00:49:29,546
from the police.

972
00:49:30,206 --> 00:49:32,907
We recorded dialogue to support both scenarios

973
00:49:33,047 --> 00:49:35,468
as time was running out, but most of it

974
00:49:35,568 --> 00:49:36,768
was for the stealth version.

975
00:49:37,409 --> 00:49:39,549
Turns out, what worked better was the latter.

976
00:49:40,390 --> 00:49:42,250
We ended up covering the majority of the chase

977
00:49:42,490 --> 00:49:43,591
using CYA lines.

978
00:49:46,488 --> 00:49:48,849
But sometimes, CYA lines aren't enough.

979
00:49:49,529 --> 00:49:52,089
We need something specific and have to borrow lines

980
00:49:52,129 --> 00:49:53,110
from another part of the game.

981
00:49:54,090 --> 00:49:55,510
So we go digging through our database

982
00:49:55,530 --> 00:49:57,411
to see what we have that can cover the request.

983
00:49:58,111 --> 00:49:59,812
When picking the line that will be duplicated,

984
00:50:00,112 --> 00:50:03,253
we take into consideration how far apart the new instance is

985
00:50:03,373 --> 00:50:05,193
from the original place the line plays,

986
00:50:05,653 --> 00:50:07,894
so that, again, the player won't notice a repeat.

987
00:50:09,860 --> 00:50:15,343
Like this moment in The Last of Us that was covered entirely through CYA lines, reused

988
00:50:15,443 --> 00:50:18,565
systemic dialogue, and a storyline of Ellie's from earlier in the game.

989
00:50:33,617 --> 00:50:36,378
There are even times we've had to change the precise timing

990
00:50:36,418 --> 00:50:38,620
of certain IGCs or cut scenes last minute,

991
00:50:39,440 --> 00:50:42,162
meaning the audio files returned from all the territories

992
00:50:42,482 --> 00:50:44,984
have to be re-edited by hand on our end.

993
00:50:46,885 --> 00:50:49,246
Our localization manager keeps painstaking track

994
00:50:49,286 --> 00:50:50,847
of all these changes so we know

995
00:50:50,867 --> 00:50:52,328
which files need the extra love.

996
00:50:54,349 --> 00:50:56,491
And by the way, tracking all of this madness

997
00:50:56,831 --> 00:50:59,893
by any means necessary is the biggest challenge

998
00:50:59,953 --> 00:51:01,314
of making things the Naughty Dog way.

999
00:51:02,209 --> 00:51:06,551
The efforts of our minimal production staff and various leads are sometimes heroic.

1000
00:51:09,192 --> 00:51:12,934
But as we near the end of production, the biggest limit on us is just time.

1001
00:51:13,754 --> 00:51:17,976
At a certain point, we can only use animations that we've captured or lines that we've recorded.

1002
00:51:18,616 --> 00:51:20,557
If we don't have the material and can't make it up,

1003
00:51:21,117 --> 00:51:26,079
sometimes that means living with tonal shifts or big cuts in material that was painstakingly shot and mocapped.

1004
00:51:27,752 --> 00:51:30,554
Back on Uncharted 1, design made a change to gameplay

1005
00:51:30,594 --> 00:51:32,355
by inserting combat into a sequence

1006
00:51:32,375 --> 00:51:34,156
that was originally just quiet traversal.

1007
00:51:34,977 --> 00:51:37,019
Nate and Elena casually walked into an area

1008
00:51:37,139 --> 00:51:38,800
in the cutscene and discovered a jet ski.

1009
00:51:39,400 --> 00:51:40,942
They weren't out of breath or recovering

1010
00:51:40,982 --> 00:51:42,363
from a tense combat situation.

1011
00:51:43,063 --> 00:51:45,945
But the gameplay needed a spike of energy for the player

1012
00:51:46,226 --> 00:51:49,028
and it worked, even though it caused a tonal mismatch

1013
00:51:49,048 --> 00:51:50,089
with the cutscene that followed.

1014
00:51:51,041 --> 00:51:53,243
Still, that late in the development process,

1015
00:51:53,403 --> 00:51:54,664
we could not reshoot the scene.

1016
00:51:55,244 --> 00:51:57,206
So this was logged as an example

1017
00:51:57,326 --> 00:51:59,127
of how we could improve maintaining tone

1018
00:51:59,167 --> 00:52:00,968
when going into a cut scene in the future.

1019
00:52:03,650 --> 00:52:06,412
On Uncharted 4, we were working on an epic sword fight

1020
00:52:06,453 --> 00:52:07,253
near the end of the game,

1021
00:52:07,794 --> 00:52:10,155
and we had planned to introduce those new mechanics

1022
00:52:10,275 --> 00:52:12,137
during the manor flashback with the kids.

1023
00:52:12,918 --> 00:52:15,700
We even mo-capped and recorded a whole bunch of material to make it happen.

1024
00:52:16,340 --> 00:52:19,741
But when we looked at the amount of work it would take to polish and script all those animations,

1025
00:52:20,062 --> 00:52:22,122
and the time we had left to finish everything else in the game,

1026
00:52:22,623 --> 00:52:24,463
our directors made a hard call and cut it.

1027
00:52:25,204 --> 00:52:27,725
So the player comes to the ending sword fight untrained,

1028
00:52:28,125 --> 00:52:30,866
and can possibly be emotionally divested from the sequence

1029
00:52:30,946 --> 00:52:33,367
as they struggle to learn new mechanics near the end of the game.

1030
00:52:36,065 --> 00:52:39,166
But if we catch an issue early enough,

1031
00:52:39,686 --> 00:52:42,468
it has been possible to make the hard choices required

1032
00:52:42,608 --> 00:52:46,370
to maintain consistent tone and performances in a sequence that

1033
00:52:46,410 --> 00:52:47,030
needs adjustment.

1034
00:52:48,951 --> 00:52:51,252
Nearing the end of The Last of Us, one of our designers

1035
00:52:51,312 --> 00:52:52,873
pointed out a big flaw we'd overlooked.

1036
00:52:53,413 --> 00:52:55,754
The Firefly Hospital culminated with a cut scene

1037
00:52:55,814 --> 00:52:58,155
where Joel charged into the operating room to save Ellie.

1038
00:52:59,207 --> 00:53:02,148
In that scene, he kills the doctor and eventually Marlene right there,

1039
00:53:02,488 --> 00:53:04,409
and we smash cut to him and Ellie driving away.

1040
00:53:05,169 --> 00:53:09,511
It was a great cut scene, and the performances we got out of it, as written, were excellent.

1041
00:53:11,352 --> 00:53:16,434
The problem was, as the designer pointed out, the player missed out on a big emotional payoff

1042
00:53:16,654 --> 00:53:20,936
that we hadn't even thought about. After carrying Joel's daughter at the beginning of the game,

1043
00:53:21,316 --> 00:53:23,877
the player was set up to expect an echo of that event.

1044
00:53:25,472 --> 00:53:27,853
that Joel would be carrying Ellie to safety at the end,

1045
00:53:28,233 --> 00:53:30,494
redeeming him some aspect of his former loss.

1046
00:53:32,135 --> 00:53:35,317
So, with some hesitation, we looked at what it might take

1047
00:53:35,397 --> 00:53:37,458
to salvage what we could from the existing cutscene.

1048
00:53:39,400 --> 00:53:42,141
By keeping the Marlene animation and just picking up Joel,

1049
00:53:42,601 --> 00:53:46,223
now carrying Ellie, we were able to move the main story beats

1050
00:53:46,243 --> 00:53:48,225
of the cutscene into the hospital parking garage.

1051
00:53:49,890 --> 00:53:52,391
This allowed for a brand new ending sequence where Joel,

1052
00:53:52,591 --> 00:53:55,273
with Joel carrying Ellie past dozens of Firefly soldiers,

1053
00:53:55,733 --> 00:53:59,736
who we were assured would refrain from shooting Joel

1054
00:54:00,136 --> 00:54:02,898
because seriously he was carrying the cure for mankind.

1055
00:54:05,499 --> 00:54:07,801
So that is what we recorded all of our dialogue for.

1056
00:54:08,521 --> 00:54:11,783
And then after localization locked, it changed again.

1057
00:54:13,275 --> 00:54:15,237
There wasn't enough tension if Joel could just walk out

1058
00:54:15,277 --> 00:54:17,479
of the hospital with Ellie, so the actions

1059
00:54:17,519 --> 00:54:19,201
of the Firefly soldiers were revamped

1060
00:54:19,281 --> 00:54:20,122
so they could attack him.

1061
00:54:20,762 --> 00:54:22,344
But that didn't match up with any

1062
00:54:22,364 --> 00:54:23,404
of the dialogue we'd recorded.

1063
00:54:26,607 --> 00:54:29,370
It took digging through NPC material we had recorded

1064
00:54:29,450 --> 00:54:31,432
for other parts of the game to make this moment

1065
00:54:31,592 --> 00:54:34,214
and the performances in it feel as equally polished

1066
00:54:34,354 --> 00:54:35,255
as others in the game.

1067
00:54:37,183 --> 00:54:39,585
ultimately was totally worth sacrificing some mocap

1068
00:54:39,645 --> 00:54:42,468
and scrambling through folders of VO to create an experience

1069
00:54:42,729 --> 00:54:44,891
that would capitalize on player empathy to that degree.

1070
00:54:47,794 --> 00:54:49,776
So we do a lot of crazy shit.

1071
00:54:51,137 --> 00:54:52,398
And I'd just like to emphasize,

1072
00:54:52,659 --> 00:54:54,260
the way we do it isn't the only way

1073
00:54:54,701 --> 00:54:57,083
or even the right way to pull off realistic performances,

1074
00:54:57,383 --> 00:54:59,986
especially depending on your team size, budget, et cetera.

1075
00:55:00,886 --> 00:55:04,169
But the level of flexibility we allow for story and gameplay

1076
00:55:04,189 --> 00:55:06,432
to influence each other during development

1077
00:55:06,832 --> 00:55:09,134
is why we feel we're able to strike a balance that we're

1078
00:55:09,154 --> 00:55:09,475
proud of.

1079
00:55:11,328 --> 00:55:13,589
And it's also why executing these performances

1080
00:55:13,709 --> 00:55:16,189
requires constant collaboration and dedication

1081
00:55:16,269 --> 00:55:18,170
from every discipline on the Naughty Dog team.

1082
00:55:18,750 --> 00:55:21,751
Writing, acting, rendering, audio, concept, character,

1083
00:55:21,831 --> 00:55:24,031
programming, animation, design, lighting, production,

1084
00:55:24,271 --> 00:55:27,092
even IT and ops, it takes a veritable metropolis

1085
00:55:27,352 --> 00:55:29,452
of talented men and women to make the performances

1086
00:55:29,712 --> 00:55:31,493
that the player can feel when the controller

1087
00:55:31,513 --> 00:55:32,073
is in their hands.

1088
00:55:34,173 --> 00:55:37,334
It is a constant struggle, but if we can truly move you

1089
00:55:37,874 --> 00:55:40,034
and maybe surprise you, then for us,

1090
00:55:40,075 --> 00:55:40,835
that's art worth making.

1091
00:55:42,025 --> 00:55:42,271
Thank you.

